english:
  title: Memorial Rite for Minister Yun
  author: Lee In-ro
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Behold the noble spirit—
    With breath pure as mountain ice,
    Character luminous as the stone qilin.

    Your writings brought auspice to the court,
    Your words and deeds embodied loyalty and truth.
    Unpolished gold and raw jade in form,
    Fitting for all uses without exception.
    Having traversed the heavens' treasuries and stone archives,
    Your wisdom knew no boundary.

    Your renown surpassed even the greatest names,
    Honor followed you like candlelight on lotus.
    You intoxicated yourself with ten thousand verses,
    Opening the very heart of Li Taibai himself.
    Forty years riding high, feasting on plenty—
    You dwelt in the abundance of Cai Gong.

    The Son of Heaven took you as his mirror,
    Scholars regarded you as a mountain to revere.
    Goodness must receive Heaven's blessing—
    All hoped to see you as minister while yet young.
    Yet why, virtuous one, did fate not grant you length of days?
    Suddenly you became attendant lord in the pale realm.

    All lament that the jade tree lies buried,
    Scholars grieve that brilliance has withered.
    In the hall remains only the mother of Chang Ji,
    Weeping blood and tears.
    In the house below, no son of Bo Dao remains—
    Who shall carry on the family name?
    No sorrow runs deeper than this.
    Why does Heaven turn away silent?

    We, your fortunate fellows, blessed to know such friendship,
    Who gathered in those gardens of jade,
    Attached ourselves to the phoenix of the Sage—
    How could we have dreamed of humbler things?
    Now we grasp the rope before your new grave,
    Pouring our sorrow into shallow cups of wine.

    The broken string hangs silent on the wall—
    No one remains to hear its notes as Zhong Ziqi heard them.
    Thunder cracks the mountain in vain—
    Only the wailing of Chang Kang echoes on.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Li Taibai (Li Bai): The great Tang dynasty poet, referenced for intoxicated verse composition.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Cai Gong: A prosperous Tang official, symbolizing wealth and high office.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Chang Ji and Bo Dao: Literary references to filial devotion and succession; their absences here underscore tragic loss.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Zhong Ziqi: A legendary figure from ancient China, the intimate friend of musician Boya, symbolizing deep understanding and friendship.'
  - key: ''
    value: The closing imagery of the broken string and thunder represents both the end of music and the inefficacy of grief against an indifferent cosmos.
